<h2>Chapter 3: 7 Content Types That Book Service Calls</h2>
<p>Most HVAC companies post the same thing: a stock photo of an air conditioner with "Call us today!" That does not work. These 7 content types do.</p>
<h3>1. Before-and-After Photos and Videos</h3>
<p>Show the old, failing system next to the clean new installation. Show a dirty filter next to a clean one. Show a rusted-out unit next to the replacement. The visual contrast is powerful. Homeowners see the transformation and think "I need that."</p>
<p><strong>Pro tip:</strong> Film a 15-second time-lapse of the installation. Post it as a Reel on Instagram and a Short on YouTube. The same video works on both platforms.</p>
<h3>2. Seasonal Maintenance Tips</h3>
<p>"3 things to check on your AC before summer." "How to prepare your furnace for winter." These posts provide genuine value and position your team as experts. They also generate saves and shares. Homeowners share maintenance tips with neighbors.</p>
<p>This content works especially well as a <a href="/blog/create-business-blog/">blog post</a> that you then share across social platforms.</p>
<h3>3. Customer Testimonials and Reviews</h3>
<p>Screenshot a 5-star Google review. Post it with a brief story about the job. Better yet, film a 30-second video testimonial with the homeowner standing next to their new system. Social proof drives bookings faster than any ad.</p>
<p>Collecting reviews consistently is critical. Our guide on <a href="/blog/ask-customers-for-reviews/">how to ask customers for reviews</a> covers the full system.</p>
<h3>4. Meet the Team</h3>
<p>Introduce each technician. Share their certification, years of experience, and a personal fact. Homeowners let HVAC techs into their homes. They want to know who is showing up. A team spotlight post builds comfort before the service call.</p>
<h3>5. Emergency Tips</h3>
<p>"What to do when your AC stops working at 10 PM." "Is that furnace smell dangerous?" Emergency content gets high engagement because it addresses urgent pain. It also positions your company as the helpful expert. When the homeowner needs a repair, they call the company that already helped them.</p>
<h3>6. Cost and Pricing Transparency</h3>
<p>"How much does a new AC unit cost in [city]?" Most homeowners research pricing before calling. A Facebook or YouTube post that answers this question honestly earns trust and captures price-sensitive leads that competitors ignore.</p>
<p>Price transparency is rare in HVAC marketing. The companies that share real pricing ranges stand out.</p>
<h3>7. Community and Local Content</h3>
<p>Sponsor a little league team. Attend a local event. Support a food drive. Post about it. Local involvement shows homeowners that your company is part of their community. That connection drives referrals and repeat business.</p>
